      <data key="d2">chunk-89777b838d5447c7bd1ec11282c4ee89</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ST. PAUL'S CHURCHYARD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">"St. Paul's Churchyard is a location mentioned metaphorically as a place where one might take a night stroll, representative of a public or notable area."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-89777b838d5447c7bd1ec11282c4ee89</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STAVE ONE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Stave One refers to the first section or part of the story, often used to denote chapters in literary works."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-89777b838d5447c7bd1ec11282c4ee89</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARLEY'S FUNERAL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Marley's Funeral is the event marking the death and burial of Marley, reinforcing his death as a significant plot point."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-89777b838d5447c7bd1ec11282c4ee89</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SCROOGE'S NEPHEW&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Scrooge's Nephew is a cheerful and warm-hearted young man who tries to spread the joy of Christmas to Scrooge despite his uncle's cold demeanor."&lt;SEP&gt;"Scrooge's Nephew is characterized by his hearty laughter, which catches Scrooge by surprise."&lt;SEP&gt;"Scrooge's nephew hosts the games and is involved in social activities where he shows a fondness for creating and maintaining merry atmospheres."&lt;SEP&gt;"Scrooge's nephew is described as a joyful, good-natured individual who frequently laughs and shows empathy towards Scrooge despite his negative opinions about Christmas."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-773d0df1dd25c356f7b771d780583e09&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-43c9bee23adfa77aa9dedd22401bba7d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-74e2466de2f67fd710ef2f20c0a8d9e0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-91614df5cb74cbe5e109a338a82041e9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THE CITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The City is a reference to where Scrooge conducts his business, indicating the contrast between his professional life and personal reflections."&lt;SEP&gt;"The City is depicted as a cold, foggy, and bleak environment during Christmas Eve, where Scrooge's counting-house is located."&lt;SEP&gt;"The City represents the broader setting where Scrooge and the Ghosts witness the impact of Christmas and Scrooge's actions."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-843b5b2f944c7413d9ca876e2e2f151f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-74e2466de2f67fd710ef2f20c0a8d9e0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8590d9263cd2cd4fa583c432fc54e6c3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SCROOGE'S CLERK&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Scrooge's Clerk works in a dismal environment with minimal heating, highlighting Scrooge's miserly nature."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-74e2466de2f67fd710ef2f20c0a8d9e0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CHRISTMAS EVE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Christmas Eve is the night before Christmas, celebrated by many, and significant in the story as a time of reflection and festivity."&lt;SEP&gt;"Christmas Eve is the time setting of the narrative, highlighting the contrast between Scrooge's disdain for the holiday and societal celebrations."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-d9aac3484185ac66045df92214d245d5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-74e2466de2f67fd710ef2f20c0a8d9e0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SCROOGE'S COUNTING-HOUSE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Scrooge's Counting-House is where Scrooge conducts his business, depicted as a frugal and cold workplace that mirrors Scrooge's personality."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-74e2466de2f67fd710ef2f20c0a8d9e0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FOG&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The fog is part of the environmental setting, representing the dreary and cold atmosphere of the city and complementing Scrooge's cold disposition."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-74e2466de2f67fd710ef2f20c0a8d9e0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NEPHEW&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Scrooge's nephew is a character who values Christmas as a time of goodwill and attempts to persuade Scrooge to join in celebrating. He is depicted as kind-hearted and persistent."&lt;SEP&gt;"Scrooge's nephew is mentioned in a conversation with the Ghost as Fan's child, creating a connection to his family."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-5dac41b3f9eeaf794f0147400b1718cd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c6c248858d1b13ab7ee9ca13c1aeed6b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CLERK&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The clerk works for Scrooge and is shown to have a warmer disposition despite difficult circumstances, like having a modest income. He inadvertently displays approval of festive sentiments."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-5dac41b3f9eeaf794f0147400b1718cd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MR. MARLEY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Mr. Marley is Scrooge's former business partner who has been dead for seven years, remembered as a kindred spirit to Scrooge in business."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-5dac41b3f9eeaf794f0147400b1718cd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PORTLY GENTLEMEN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The portly gentlemen are characters who appeal to Scrooge for charity towards the impoverished during the festive season. They are depicted as pleasant and earnest."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-5dac41b3f9eeaf794f0147400b1718cd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SCROOGE AND MARLEY'S&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Scrooge and Marley's is the business firm formerly run by Scrooge and Marley, suggesting an established enterprise where Scrooge still works as the surviving partner."&lt;SEP&gt;"Scrooge and Marley's is the counting-house formerly run by Scrooge, indicating his status as a businessman."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-8f738cb25d60a7dab782162d9d0a25ed&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5dac41b3f9eeaf794f0147400b1718cd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CHRISTMAS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Christmas is a recurring event in the text, serving as both an occasion for celebration and a source of contention between characters. It is depicted as a time for reflection, goodwill, and charitable actions."&lt;SEP&gt;"Christmas is an event that appears frequently in Scrooge's memories, particularly linked to themes of joy, neglect, and the contrast of past and present feelings."&lt;SEP&gt;"Christmas is celebrated as a joyful and festive occasion, with decorations and family gatherings."&lt;SEP&gt;"Christmas is portrayed as a significant time of reflection and memory for Scrooge, evoking feelings of regret, sadness, and nostalgia."&lt;SEP&gt;"Christmas is the backdrop of the story, a festive time that elicits memories and reflections for Scrooge."&lt;SEP&gt;"Christmas is the central festive event during which the characters gather for celebration and games, fostering communal joy and reflection."&lt;SEP&gt;"Christmas is the central holiday being celebrated, representing warmth, generosity, and the spirit of giving that contrasts with Scrooge’s initial demeanor."&lt;SEP&gt;"Christmas is the festive season during which the narrative takes place, highlighting themes of charity, celebration, and introspection."&lt;SEP&gt;"Christmas serves as the backdrop for the joyful family gathering and gift-giving scene."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-1d4b58de5429cd1261370c231c8673e8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-43c9bee23adfa77aa9dedd22401bba7d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5dac41b3f9eeaf794f0147400b1718cd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-da2472b4ef2a535b62908f14d0fb0ca9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-90d5764e301321c087f5a8f78b73a145&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-843b5b2f944c7413d9ca876e2e2f151f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c6c248858d1b13ab7ee9ca13c1aeed6b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bb21d58d36c6306fd8810ddd51c4a971&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8590d9263cd2cd4fa583c432fc54e6c3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BEDLAM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Bedlam is referenced by Scrooge in a figurative sense to express frustration, referring to a historical institution known for housing the mentally ill, representing a place of chaos or madness."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-5dac41b3f9eeaf794f0147400b1718cd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THE GENTLEMAN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Gentleman interacts with Scrooge, attempting to collect donations for the poor, highlighting the charitable efforts during Christmas."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-90d5764e301321c087f5a8f78b73a145</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;UNION WORKHOUSES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Union Workhouses were institutions in Victorian England meant to provide shelter and work for the poor, often criticized for their harsh conditions."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-90d5764e301321c087f5a8f78b73a145</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THE TREADMILL AND THE POOR LAW&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Treadmill and The Poor Law refer to measures in place in Victorian England aimed at dealing with poverty, often seen as punitive rather than supportive."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-90d5764e301321c087f5a8f78b73a145</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MANSION HOUSE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Mansion House is the official residence of the Lord Mayor of London, symbolizing authority and tradition."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-90d5764e301321c087f5a8f78b73a145</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THE LORD MAYOR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Lord Mayor is a ceremonial position representing the head of the City of London, responsible for overseeing official functions and events, especially during Christmas."</data>
      <data key="d2">chunk-90d5764e301321c087f5a8f78b73a145</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ST. DUNSTAN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
